"London, England","Anjou, France":"Anjou, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ferrers","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: locative name from Ferrières-Saint-Hilaire (Eure) and Ferrières (Manche)."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferris","meanings":["Irish and Scottish: shortened Anglicized form of Irish <b>Ó Fearghuis</b> or <b>Ó Fearghasa</b> ‘descendant of <i>Fearghus</i>’, or from the Scottish-Gaelic form of this personal name, <i>Fearghus</i> (see   Fergus  ).","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Ferrières-Saint-Hilaire, Eure and Ferrières, La Manche in Normandy, France."]},{"name":"Ferridge","meanings":["English: unexplained; possibly a form of  <i>Ferris</i> and therefore a variant of   Ferrers  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":37,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Robert Ferrers was born in 1345, in Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom. He married Joan de Beaufort in 1391, in Anjou, France. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. He died on 29 November 1396, in Willisham, Suffolk, England, at the age of 51, and was buried in London, England."},"et":{"1345–29 November 1396":"1345–29. november 1396","1375–1440":"1375–1440","1394–1457":"1394–1457","–1460":"–1460","1345–1396":"1345–1396","29 November 1396":"29. november 1396","1457":"1457","1345":"1345","1375":"1375","1396":"1396","1440":"1440","1375/79":"1375","December 1380":"detsember 1380","1394":"1394","1460":"1460","1382":"1382","1391":"1391","Willisham, Suffolk, England":"Willisham, Suffolk, England","Stratford on Avon, Warwickshire, England":"Stratford on Avon, Warwickshire, England","Chartley, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","London, England":"London, England","Anjou, France":"Anjou, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1345–29 November 1396":"1345–29. marraskuuta 1396","1375–1440":"1375–1440","1394–1457":"1394–1457","–1460":"–1460","1345–1396":"1345–1396","29 November 1396":"29. marraskuuta 1396","1457":"1457","1345":"1345","1375":"1375","1396":"1396","1440":"1440","1375/79":"1375","December 1380":"joulukuu 1380","1394":"1394","1460":"1460","1382":"1382","1391":"1391","Willisham, Suffolk, England":"Willisham, Suffolk, England","Stratford on Avon, Warwickshire, England":"Stratford on Avon, Warwickshire, England","Chartley, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Staffordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","London, England":"London, England","Anjou, France":"Anjou, Ranska"},"fr":{"1345–29 No